      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Modern historians view the UN's effectiveness in stopping major wars in the 21st century as a qualified failure, largely due to the persistent veto power of the Security Council's permanent members. While the UN excels at humanitarian aid and conflict mediation in smaller crises, its inability to enforce peace when great power interests clash renders it toothless against large-scale aggression. Therefore, its impact is often limited to mitigating the worst outcomes rather than preventing the wars themselves.",
